[{"id":30901,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is true but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Statement I,</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>SnO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>PbO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mtext>Amphoteric</mtext><mo> </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>GeO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>GeO</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mtext>Acidic</mtext><mo> </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>CO</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mtext> Neutral</mtext></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to Statement II,<br/>Carbon does not have d-orbitals so can not form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pπ</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>dπ</mi></math> Bond with itself. Due to properties of catenation and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pπ</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>pπ</mi></math> bond formation, carbon is able to show allotropic forms. Allotropic forms of carbon can be crystalline and amorphous.<br/>Diamond and graphite are two well-known crystalline forms of carbon. </p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence option C is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30966,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{R}_4 \\mathrm{Si}$","$\\mathrm{RSiCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{SiCl}_2$","$\\mathrm{R}_3 \\mathrm{SiCl}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Grirfz9bpZV5zvAdjRrkjQ90J4tVOb0CpuxzLjqsb-k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30945,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>≈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>≈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">G</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Carbon atom&nbsp;have the tendency to link with one another through covalent bonds to form chains because of its tetra valency. This property is called catenation tendency. Carbon shows maximum catenation tendency among its group elements due to its high bond enthalpy. As we go down, the group size increases and electronegativity decreases therefore catenation tendency decreases.<br />&nbsp;So,order of catenation tendency is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mi>Sn</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30905,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Both (A) and (R) are correct but (R) Is not the correct explanation of (A)","Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)","(A) is true but (R) is false","(A) is false but (R) is true"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Boron is non-metallic in nature. It is extremely hard and black coloured solid. Due to a very strong crystalline lattice, boron has an unusually high melting point. The rest of the members are soft metals with a low melting point and high electrical conductivity.</p><p>Hence, Solid Boron has very strong crystalline lattice, so its melting point is unusually high in group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn></math> elements.</p><p>Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R) is the correct explanation of (A)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30973,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["developing interlocking needle-like crystals of hydrated silicates","hydrating sand and gravel mixed with cement","converting sand into silicic acid","keeping it cool"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":30918,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Co</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>BO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CoB</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Co</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>On heating, borax loses its water of crystallisation and decomposes to give sodium metaborate and boric anhydride</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>10</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NaBO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> (sodium meta borate)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>On treatment with metal salt, boric anhydride forms metaborate of the metal which gives different colours in oxidising and reducing flame. For example, in the case of copper sulphate, following reactions occur</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>CoO</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Co</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>BO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (cobalt <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;metaborate)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Blue Bead</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30908,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The crude name of borax is Tincal. It has the molecular formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><mn>10</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;and structural formula of&nbsp;borax is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>Based on the structural formula,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>17</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30925,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math> gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>BO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> (strong base) in water.</p><p>So, it is a salt of strong base and weak acid. So, its&nbsp;solution will be strongly basic in water. It will have very high pH.</p><p><span style=\"background-color:null;\">Lithium borohydride&nbsp;and sodium borohydride&nbsp;reacts with water&nbsp;to produce hydrogen.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:null;\">And diborane act as lewis acid.</span></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30939,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaN</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi></mover><mi>PbO</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;gas is constituent of air and it produces ammonia gas (basic nature) after reacting with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;gas.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>NaN</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo></math>give nitrogen gas on heating but lead nitrate doesn&#39;t give nitrogen gas so it will be answer.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaN</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mn>300</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mover><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30896,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["3","2","1","4"],"answer":1,"solution":"Due to inert pair effect; $\\mathrm{T} \\ell^{+3}$ and $\\mathrm{Pb}^{+4}$ can behave as oxidising agents.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30952,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> has <math><mn>2</mn></math> bridge bonds <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math><mn>4</mn></math> terminal bonds <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>.<br />&nbsp; <img height=\"130\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e0a668b0-5446-4454-b53b-9cd74cd0b713-image.png\" width=\"358\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30887,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["C and D Only","A and D Only","A and C Only","B and D Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Analyzing statements about Group 13 elements (B, Al, Ga, In, Tl):<br>A. Ionic radii of M³⁺ cations: Down a group, more electron shells are added, so ionic radii increase, not decrease. FALSE<br>B. Electronegativity: Generally decreases down the group, though Ga shows an anomaly with higher electronegativity than Al. The statement is approximately true but has exceptions.<br>C. First ionization enthalpy: B (800.6 kJ/mol) is highest due to smallest size and highest nuclear charge density. Al (577.5), Ga (579), In (558), Tl (589). TRUE<br>D. Trichlorides and triodides: BCl₃, AlCl₃, GaCl₃, etc. are all covalent compounds (electron-deficient). BI₃, AlI₃, GaI₃, etc. are also covalent (I⁻ is large and polarizable). TRUE<br>The clearly correct statements are C and D.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30915,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Both the statements I and II are correct","Statement I&nbsp;is incorrect but statement II is correct","Both the statements I and II are incorrect","Statement I is correct but statement II is incorrect"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Statement-I is correct.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ni</mi></math>(Nickel) is used in Hydrogenation of unsaturated fat to make edible fats to convert unsaturated compounds to saturated compounds.</p><p>Statements-II is false as hydride of Silicon is electron precise &amp; neither electron deficient nor electron rich.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30911,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Si</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Ge</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Si</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Sn</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Ge</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Sn</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>As bond length increases, bond energy decreases.</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 400px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><strong>Bond</strong></td>\t\t\t<td><strong>Bond energy (kJ mol<sup>-1</sup>)</strong></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>C - C</td>\t\t\t<td>348</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Si - Si</td>\t\t\t<td>297</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Ge - Ge</td>\t\t\t<td>260</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Sn - Sn</td>\t\t\t<td>240</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>So, bond enthalpy order&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Si</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Ge</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Sn</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30951,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Al}  < \\mathrm{Ga} < \\mathrm{Tl} < \\mathrm{In}$","$\\mathrm{T} 1  < \\mathrm{In} < \\mathrm{Ga} < \\mathrm{Al}$","$\\mathrm{Ga}  < \\mathrm{Al} < \\ln < \\mathrm{Tl}$","$\\mathrm{Al}  < \\mathrm{Ga} < \\mathrm{In} < \\mathrm{Tl}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Due to inert pair effect, the stability of +1 oxidation\r\n\r\nstate increases down the group. Thus, correct order of stability is $\\mathrm{Al}  < \\mathrm{Ga} < \\mathrm{In} < \\mathrm{Tl}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30940,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Bogging god <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","Diborane and <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","Boron nitride and <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","Borazine and <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The reaction of <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math> in tetrahydrofuran gives inorganic benzene <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>. The reaction is given below.&nbsp;&nbsp;Further, the reaction of compound&nbsp;&nbsp;<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;reacts&nbsp;with <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> leads to <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> .</p><p>The reaction is given beow:</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>LiBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#10230;</mo><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>+</mo><mi>LiCI</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>BCI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>MeMgBr</mi></mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></munder><mo>&#10230;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>MgBrCI</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30919,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;is the correct explanation of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;is not the correct explanation of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;is false","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>&nbsp;is true"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Due to non-availability of d orbitals, boron is unable to expand its octet. Therefore, the maximum covalence of boron cannot exceed&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>.</p><p>Boron is the first element from top in group&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn></math>&nbsp;and the atomic size increases down the group. Therefore, boron is smallest in size.</p><p>Assertion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>: True</p><p>Reason <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math>: True but not correct explanation.<br />&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30941,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["zinc sulphide","Mercury","Silicon carbide","Carbon tetrachloride"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Carbon tetrachloride boils at low temperatures and is a non-conductor in both solid and liquid phases.&nbsp;Carbon tetrachloride is made up of individual covalently bonded molecules, CCl<sub>4</sub>. Therefore, the electrons&nbsp;cannot&nbsp;flow and there are&nbsp;no&nbsp;ions. So it&nbsp;does not conduct&nbsp;in any state.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30958,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Reaction of lithium hydride with <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></math>.","Electrolysis of acidified water using <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>electrodes.","Reaction of zinc with aqueous alkali.","Allowing a solution of sodium in liquid ammonia to stand."],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>LiH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>react with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> to produce boron lithium hydride.<br />The reaction proceeds in the medium of ester and complex form.<br /><br /><math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>]</mo></math><br /><br />So do not liberate <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> gas.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30935,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Pb</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PbSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is amphoteric and strong oxidizing agent and also a component of lead storage batteries.</p><p>In lead storage batteries <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is used. In this Oxidation state&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></math> so, it is always reduced and behaves as oxidizing agent</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30893,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["$+4$ and +1","+1 and +4","+4 and +3","+2 and +3"],"answer":2,"solution":"Among $\\mathrm{Al}, \\mathrm{In}, \\mathrm{Tl}, \\mathrm{Ge}, \\mathrm{Sn}, \\mathrm{Pb}$, the metal having highest $\\mathrm{IE}_1$ is Ge and lowest $\\mathrm{IE}_1$ is In .\nMost stable oxidation state of Ge is +4 and In is +3 .","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30962,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["LiAlH<sub>4</sub> is versatile reducing agent in organic synthesis.","NO<sup>+ </sup>is isoelectronic&nbsp;with O<sub>2</sub>","Boron is always covalent in its compounds","In aqueous solution, the Tl<sup>+</sup> ion is much more stable than Tl (III)"],"answer":1,"solution":"(i) LiAlH<sub>4</sub>&nbsp;is a versatile reducing agent<br />(ii) NO<sup>+</sup> (14 electrons), O<sub>2</sub>(16 electrons) not isoelectronic<br />(iii) ​Tl<sup>+ </sup>is more stable due to Inert pair effect<br />(iv) Boron compounds are ionic as well&nbsp;<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>B</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <msub> <mtext>O</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>NaOH</mo> <mo>&#8594;</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msub> <mo>NaBO</mo> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>H</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>O</mtext> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(Sodium meta Borate)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30917,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A.","Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A.","A is not correct but R &nbsp;&nbsp;is correct.&nbsp;","A&nbsp;&nbsp;is correct but R &nbsp;is not correct.&nbsp;"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Carbon monoxide (CO) is neutral and carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) is acidic in nature because with the increase in the oxidation state carbon&#39;s acidic strength increases. So, the Assertion is correct</p><p>CO<sub>2</sub> combines with water to form carbonic acid while CO is sparingly soluble in water. So, Reason is also correct and is the correct explanation of Assertion.</p><p>So, correct option is B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30936,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["All <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> angles are of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","The two <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> bonds&nbsp;(bridged and terminal)&nbsp;are not of same length.","Terminal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> bonds have less <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> -character when compared to bridging bonds.","Its fragment, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;behaves as a Lewis acid."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/92ffe039-7478-4f7c-994c-406d7fa532bc-image.png\" style=\"width: 370px; height: 152px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>&nbsp;(terminal)&nbsp;having less <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math><br />character as compare to bridge bond.</p><p>Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;(bridge bond and terminal bond) do not&nbsp;have&nbsp;same bond length.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> bond angle is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is electron&nbsp;deficient&nbsp; species and therefore acts as Lewis acid</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30904,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Gr</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mi>EN</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Si</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ge</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Sn</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The electronegativity values for elements from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Si</mi></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi></math> are almost same. So Statement I is false.</p><ol> <li>Among them, Carbon and silicon are non-metals.</li> <li>Germanium is metalloid in nature</li> <li>Tin and lead are metal.</li></ol><p>Reason for different metallic characteristics</p><ol> <li>The metallic character increases down the group from carbon to lead as nonmetal to metal.</li> <li>The metallic character increases because the atomic size increases from Carbon to Lead.</li> <li>As size increases, the ionization potential decreases down the group.</li> <li>A decrease in ionization potential lead to an increase in the electropositive character of the element.</li></ol><p>Hence, the metallic character increases down the group in group<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></math> as the ionization potential decreases to make it easier to lose an electron and increase the metallic character.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30944,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math><mn>12</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>20</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>4</mn></math>","<math><mn>20</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>12</mn></math>  and  <math><mn>4</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn></mrow></msub></math> is a molecule that consists of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> atoms, arranged as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math> pentagons and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math> hexagons.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b593135-273a-461a-a69c-bb3d8894f67f-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 211px;\" /><br />It has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> trigons.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30903,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>GeO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>GeO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>GeO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>CO</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>All members of group 14 when heated in oxygen form oxides. There are mainly two types of oxides, i.e., monoxide and dioxide of formula <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> respectively. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>SiO</mi></math> only exists at high temperature. Oxides in higher oxidation states of elements are generally more acidic than those in lower oxidation states. The dioxides <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>GeO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> are acidic, whereas <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PbO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> are amphoteric in nature. Amongst monoxides, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi></math> is neutral.</p><p>Hence option C is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30955,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{LiCl}, \\mathrm{AlH}_3$ and $\\mathrm{SiH}_4$","$\\mathrm{LiCl}, \\mathrm{AlCl}_3$ and $\\mathrm{SiH}_4$","$\\mathrm{LiH}, \\mathrm{AlCl}_3$ and $\\mathrm{SiCl}_2$","$\\mathrm{LiH}, \\mathrm{AlH}_3$ and $\\mathrm{SiH}_4$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{SiCl}_4+\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{LiCl}+\\mathrm{AlCl}_3+\\mathrm{SiH}_4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":30964,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{BH}_4^{-}$","$\\mathrm{B}(\\mathrm{OH})_4^{-}$","$\\mathrm{BO}_2^{-}$","$\\mathrm{BF}_6^{3-}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"As Boron has only four orbitals in the valence shell ( i.e. $2 s, 2 p_x, 2 p_y \\& 2 p_z$ ) it can show a maximum valency of four only.\nTherefore $\\left[\\mathrm{BF}_6\\right]^{3-}$ is not possible","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":30949,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"p Block Elements (Group 13 & 14)","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> and <math><msup><mrow><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>]</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Diborane reacts with oxygen exothermically to form boric oxide <math><mo>(</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>)</mo></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>  <br/>Diborane gets readily hydrolysed to give boric acid <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null}]